Ah—I misread the model. No, actually your current $12 one-time per use structure is NOT the right choice for profitability. Let me explain why and what you should do instead.

Why One-Time $12 Per Use Hurts Profitability
The Math:
Your current model:

Freelancer generates compliance package: $12 (one-time)
Customer sees: "Great deal!"
Your LTV: $12 (one-time, never returns)
Your LTV:CAC ratio: Terrible (CAC to acquire them = ~$5–15, you only make $12 total)
Problem: Customers don't generate packages every week. A freelancer scans their website ONCE per project, maybe once per year for updates. So:

Month 1: 100 freelancers × $12 = $1,200
Month 2: 0 revenue from Month 1 customers (they don't need another scan)
Month 3: New 100 freelancers × $12 = $1,200
Monthly churn: 100% (no repeat revenue)
MRR: Flatlines at whatever your new user acquisition is
This is a unit economics disaster.

What You Should Do Instead: Hybrid Model
Keep the $12 one-time as a loss leader / entry point, but restructure into:

Option A: Tiered Freemium → Subscription Upsell ✅ RECOMMENDED
